Jamaica Ave., south side, between 166th and 168th Streets, showing in a set of four views some very old homes. In View No. 4 at the extreme right is the general merchandise store conducted by Samuel Hirst from 1873 to 1891. His former place of business was at 124 Fulton Street in 1883. This business was originally started by his father in 1823. See other views for more data.

(1) Jamaica Ave. (Elevated B.M.T. line thereon), south side between 166th and 168th Streets, showing a rear view of some old homes. At the left was the Hurst home from 1873-1891, occupied by the A & P Company in 1922. The address of this place was, old No. 466 Jamaica Ave. A. Duryea was owner of the middle house for the same period (1873-1891); now occupied by a barber shop. The house at the right (474-476 Jamaica Ave.) was demolished in 1924. M. Meegan and Jacob Smith were the owners in 1873 and 1891 respectively.

About 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

The same showing another view of this area.

April 1, 1932.

P. L. Sperr.

Jamaica Ave., (Elevated B.M.T. line thereon), south side, between 166th and 168th Streets, showing in a set of four views the rears of some old homes. At the extreme left partially shown was the Hurst home from 1873 to 1891. It also was at one time the K. Stenupf hotel. A. Duryea occupied the center house in the same period. The house on the right is the Jacob Smith homestead, said to be about One Hundred and Fifty years old. It was purchased by Mrs. Mary Meegan in 1873 and later owned by her daughter, Mrs. Catherine Kammerer. The house was sold in 1924, and demolished in October of the same year.

January 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Hillside Avenue, at 166th Street, looking north along the latter, showing the Victory Monument, erected to commemorate the victory of the Union armies over the Confederacy in the Civil War.

Ewing Galloway
About 1927

92-52 166th Street, west side, between Jamaica and Douglas Avenues, just north of the Long Island Railroad. The house appears on Wolverton's 1891 map but its ownership is not indicated. 165th Street, here, was known as Smith Street.

P. L. Sperr

April 6, 1932

92-58 and 92-52 166th Street, west side, between Jamaica and Douglas Avenues, north of the Long Island Railroad, showing two old brick homes. They appear on the 1891 atlas of Jamaica.

P. L. Sperr
April 6, 1932

Jamaica Ave. (elevated structure thereon), at the N.W. corner of 166th Street, showing a frame structure erected by T.F. Archer, who owned it in 1891. In 1931 Ludwig Baumann's six-story building and Loew's Valencia Theatre occupied the site.

March 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
